OM380.17 - MSBA: Assignment #2

Forecasting Aggregate Electricity Generation in the US:

Seasonal ARIMA Lab.

(Total 40 pts.)

Due: Nov. 20 (before 9:00am)

In this assignment we will focus on estimation of electricity generation in the US through December 2022. We will base our analysis on the monthly data (index) provided by the Federal Reserve in https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/IPG2211N

library(fpp)
library(dplyr)

PG <- read.csv("IPG2211N.csv") %>%
  select(-DATE) %>%
  ts(start=c(1972,1), frequency=12)
plot(PG)
abline(v=c(2005,1), col="gray")

Initially we will set up as training data the series from January 1972 through December 1995, and the testing set as the data from January 1996 through December 2000. First we will analyze the data during the growth period. To maintain consistency across the class, please execute the following two command to generate the training and testing data sets as indicated:

PG1.tr <- window(PG, end=c(1995,12))
PG1.te <- window(PG, start=c(1996,1), end=c(2000,12))

  • Use the ggtsdisplay(…, lag=48) function to examine ACF and PACF of the Box-Cox transformed series with a non-seasonal difference. Do the differenced and transformed series look stationary?

#ggtsdisplay(z,lag = 48)
z %>% diff(1) %>% ggtsdisplay(lag=48)

The above series revolves around a constant mean but the variance is changing in seasonal patterns. Thus we can apply a seasonal difference (at lag = 12) to make it more stationary

Using the ADF test to check for stationary property

d <- z %>% diff(1) 
adf.test(d, alternative = 'stationary', k =12)
p-value smaller than printed p-value

    Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test

data:  d
Dickey-Fuller = -5.2335, Lag order = 12, p-value = 0.01
alternative hypothesis: stationary

The ADF test is showing it as stationary, but looking at the ACF and the series plot (which is not looking as a white noise) it does not seems that it is stationary

Also, we can see a spike at 36 => P would be 3; also q = 9 ; Q = 4 ; p=9

  • Use the ggtsdisplay(…, lag=48) function to examine ACF and PACF of the Box-Cox transformed series with a seasonal difference. Do the differenced and transformed series look stationary?

z %>% diff(lag = 12) %>% ggtsdisplay(lag=48)

The series is showing some trend , thus the mean does not look constant. Also, the variance is also not constant across the lags. In the ACF plot, we can see a systematic decrease in the lags, but in the PACF it cuts off until certain times. Thus the resultant series does look stationary

If at all we want to fit arima on this series, following would be the parameters:

p = 6; since if we go till 9, significant till 6; Similarly P = 2 ; q = 8 ; Q = 2

  • Use the ggtsdisplay(…, lag=48) function to examine ACF and PACF of the Box-Cox transformed series with both a seasonal difference and a non-seasonal difference. Do the differenced and transformed series look stationary?

Ideally I would want to check for p -> 0:9, q-> 0:9, P-> 0:4 and similarly for Q. But it is becoming very much computationally heavy. Thus to make it computationally light, I will just be checking it with Auto Arima’s AIC value in the previous question, since you will be missing one data point.

for(i in 1:9){
  #print(pval[i])
  for(j in 1:9 ){
    
    for(k in 1:5){
      for(l in 1:5){
      counter = counter+1
      #print(counter)
      tryCatch({ 
        
      p <- pval[i]
      q <- qval[j]
      Q <- Qval[k]
      P <- Pval[l]
      train <- PG1.tr %>% Arima(order= c(p,0,q), seasonal= c(P,1,Q), lambda = L)
      trainAic <- train$aic
      trainBic <- train$bic
       
      if(trainAic < q2$aic & trainBic < q2$bic )
      {
      print("test")
      aicflag <- trainAic
      trainAICc <- train$aicc
      trainBIC <- train$bic
      forecast_train <- forecast(train,h=60)
      
      forecast_train_summ <- accuracy(forecast_train,PG1.te)
      
      train_mape <- forecast_train_summ[2,5]
      train_mase <- forecast_train_summ[2,6]
      
      frcst_arry <- rbind(frcst_arry,c(trainAic,trainAICc,trainBIC,train_mape,train_mase,p[1],0,q[1],P[1],1,Q[1]))
      break 
      }
      
      }, error = function(e){ })
                next

      q <- qval[j]

## Using grid search to calculate the training AICc, BIC and AIC. Also, looking for RMSE, MAPE, MASE in the test set

qval <- c(0,1,2)

Pval <- c(0,1,2)
dval <- c(0,1,2)
Dval <- c(0,1,2)

frcst_arry7 <- data.frame()
counter = 0
for(i in 1:3){
  #print(pval[i])
  for(j in 1:3 ){
    for(k in 1:2){
      for(l in 1:2){
          for(n in 1:3){
            for(o in 1:3){
              
                p <- pval[i]
                q <- qval[j]
                Q <- Qval[k]
                P <- Pval[l]
                d <- dval[n]
                D <- Dval[o]
                counter = counter +1 
                
          
                  
                  tryCatch({
                  train <-  PG3.tr %>% Arima(order= c(p,d,q), seasonal= c(P,D,Q)) 
                  #train <-  PG3.tr %>% Arima(order= c(p,d,q), seasonal= c(P,D,Q)) 
                  
                
                trainAic <- train$aic
                trainAICc <- train$aicc
                trainBIC <- train$bic
                forecast_train <- forecast(train,h=60)
                forecast_train_summ <- accuracy(forecast_train,PG3.te)
                train_mape <- forecast_train_summ[2,5]
                train_mase <- forecast_train_summ[2,6]
                
                frcst_arry7 <- rbind(frcst_arry7,c(trainAic,trainAICc,trainBIC,train_mape,train_mase,p[1],d[1],q[1],P[1],D[1],Q[1]))
                  }, error = function(e){ })
                next
                
            }
          }  
        }
      } 
    }
  }
